The `HashMap` relies in part on `equals` and `hashCode` to do its work, but it is a bit more complicated. Take a look at [this article](http://javahungry.blogspot.com/2013/08/hashing-how-hash-map-works-in-java-or.html) for an in depth explanation.

For your purose (Map with a list as its value), I suggest the use of [`Multimap`](http://docs.guava-libraries.googlecode.com/git/javadoc/com/google/common/collect/Multimap.html) from Google&#39;s Guava library:

    ListMultimap&lt;Integer, String&gt; multimap = ArrayListMultimap.create();
    multimap.put(4, &quot;Is the first digit of &#39;4&#39;&quot;);
    multimap.put(4, &quot;Is the first digit of &#39;42&#39;&quot;);
    multimap.put(4, &quot;Is the first digit of &#39;4711&#39;&quot;);
    multimap.put(1, &quot;Is the first digit of &#39;13&#39;&quot;);
    
    Collection&lt;String&gt; values = multimap.get(4);

The `Collection` `values` will contain the three elments that you added under the key `4`.

**Check that the value you overgive to `map.get(value)` is exactly the type of the key of the map** - in my example below either int or Integer, but neither long, Long, byte, ... nor Byte.

I found this post, when I had a similar problem by e. g. calling  `getText(5);` the method returned `null`!
But no answer and comment helped me. But finally I saw the problem:

    package ch.omwo.common.german.numbers;
    
    import java.util.HashMap;
    
    public class NumberConverter {
    
    	public String getText(long number) { // with long it does not work, with int it works!
    		
    		HashMap&lt;Integer, String&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;Integer, String&gt;()
    		{
    			{
    					put(1, &quot;eins&quot;        );
    					put(2, &quot;zwei&quot;        );
    					put(3, &quot;drei&quot;        );
    					put(4, &quot;vier&quot;        );
    					put(5, &quot;f&#252;nf&quot;        );
    					put(6, &quot;sechs&quot;       );
    					put(7, &quot;sieben&quot;      );
    					put(8, &quot;acht&quot;        );
    					put(9, &quot;neun&quot;        );
    					put(10, &quot;zehn&quot;       );
    			}
    		};
    		
    		return map.get(number); // this is defined as: public V get(Object key)
    	}
    }

If I looked into the code - `Integer.hashCode(5)` and `Long.hashCode(5)` deliver the same hashcode for 5 -&gt; 5.    

    public static int hashCode(int value) {
           return value;
    }

    public static int hashCode(long value) {
        return (int)(value ^ (value &gt;&gt;&gt; 32));
    }

Because `map.get(Object key)` expects an Object, the long value 5 will be boxed into an Object of type **L**ong with value 5.
Inside the code the hash is right, but the next step is comparing the Integer key with  `==` to the Long object. 
Here I am not sure, whether it will take reference comparision (that would fail anyway) or `equals`, where this code comes from Integer class:

    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if (obj instanceof Integer) {
            return value == ((Integer)obj).intValue();
        }
        return false;
    }

The parameter `obj` is no instance of Integer (but Long) and therefore `equals` will return false and `map.get` finally `null`.

That was the reason of my &quot;bug&quot;.

**In this case no implicit type conversion occurs! Only boxing.**

