Each thread has an interrupted status that is used as a boolean flag. When someone would like to interrupt a thread, this flag is set to true. There is no precise definition of what interruption means, but it is generally used as a signal for cancellation. 

A thread can get interrupted either while running and doing some work or while waiting/sleeping (in `WAITING` or a `TIMED_WAITING` state). 

1) If interrupted while running, only the interrupted flag is set to true and nothing else. So logically if you want to cancel your job you should keep checking this value:

```
Callable&lt;V&gt; task = () -&gt; {
    while (more work to do) {
        if (Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted()) return null;
        // Do more work
    }
    return result;
};
```

2) If interrupted while in wait/sleep status an InterruptedException is thrown (and interrupted state is cleared, so if you check the flag within the catch block it will be false). Examples of these methods are: wait(), Thread.sleep(), BlockingQueue.get(), Semaphore.acquire() and Thread.join().

So if a method is known as uninterruptible, then you can expect that it is not going to throw an exception but will set the interrupted flag to true and continue running. You could take a look at the semaphore example with `acquire` and `acquireUninterruptibly`:

```
static class SemaphoreBlocked implements Runnable {

        Semaphore semaphore = new Semaphore(0);
        @Override
        public void run() {
            try {
                semaphore.acquire();
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                log.info(&quot;Semaphore interrupted, {}&quot;, Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted());
                throw new RuntimeException(e);
            }
        }
    }

static class SemaphoreBlockedUninterruptibly implements Runnable {

        Semaphore semaphore = new Semaphore(0);
        @Override
        public void run() {
            semaphore.acquireUninterruptibly();
            System.out.println(&quot;Exiting&quot;);
        }
}
    
```

